## Version 2.6 - 2026-02-22

### Changed
- Launch and Live-Code controls:
  - Replace default launch dropdown behavior with a custom controls bar (`📓`, `▶`/`A`, `⚙`).
  - Add user settings panel for:
    - Jupyter notebook execution environment (`Datahub HM` / `Binder`)
    - Live Code activation mode (`manual` / `auto`)
  - Keep settings persisted in browser storage (`localStorage`).
  - Default settings:
    - JupyterHub selection: `Datahub HM`
    - Live Code mode: `manual`
  - Keep launch controls visible and represent unavailable states as disabled buttons (instead of hiding controls).
  - Use unified green active styling for both `📓` and `▶`; disabled states remain grey.
  - Use `A` (disabled) badge on pages where live code is in automatic mode and executable content is available.

- Launch behavior:
  - Show `📓` as enabled only when a valid launch target is available (Binder or Datahub link found on page).
  - Keep `📓` disabled when no launch target exists.
  - Update launch target dynamically when hub preference changes in settings.

- Live Code behavior:
  - In `manual` mode, show `▶` enabled only when a launch target is available.
  - In `auto` mode, disable `▶`; auto-bootstrap live code on page load.
  - Restrict auto-bootstrap attempts to pages with launch targets to avoid unnecessary load on Binder/Datahub.
  - Ensure hub switch does not interrupt an already running live-code session.

- UI/UX details:
  - Upgrade settings button from text to larger gear icon (`⚙`).
  - Upgrade launch action from text button to icon (`📓`).
  - Upgrade manual live-code action from text button to icon (`▶`).
  - Close settings panel on click outside and on `Escape`.
  - Improve accessibility labels/tooltips for control states.

- Stability and performance:
  - Prevent mutation-observer feedback loops in `user-settings.js`.
  - Throttle DOM refresh work via animation-frame scheduling to avoid timeout-related page stalls.

- Documentation alignment (content update pending in chapter text):
  - Planned wording/UI alignment in:
    - `chapters/01-course-overview/1-1-1-Live-Code.md`
    - `chapters/01-course-overview/1-1-2-Python-Beispiele.md`
    - `chapters/01-course-overview/1-1-3-Live-Code-Alternative-mit-Debugging.md`


